snippet.textDisplay: For a bit on military tactics, during the Battle of Gettysburg, the Union employed a fish hook formation. Normally you don't want an opposing army to surround you with a concave, but the US were defensively positioned on relatively higher ground. One advantage of the fish hook formation is being able to reinforce fronts in anticipation of incoming charges. They have formal tours as well as self-guided tours at Gettysburg. There's a TON of monuments across the town, which serve as landmarks for the various skirmishes and units involved.

snippet.textDisplay: To complicate your excellently simple video a tad, Sherman's March Through Georgia (and S.C.) was not just designed to inflict economic hardship on civilians.  He hoped it would convince Confederate soldiers to desert to return home to protect their families.  (Mongering that fear was one reason he freed so many slaves.)  This was a spectacular success, as many more Confederates deserted during these months than became casualties during the rest of the war.  Sherman saved 10s of thousands of lives on both sides.
